      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Blockages in the pitot tube can indeed cause issues for pilots, as it can give them an inaccurate airspeed reading. Some common culprits include ice, snow, or other debris that can clog the tube, or even insects like bees or wasps that might get sucked into the tube. In particularly bad weather conditions, like fog or heavy rain, even small particles like water droplets or dust can accumulate on the tube. These blockages can lead to a sticky-hold situation for the aircraft, making it difficult to control speed and altitude.",
